Various SAS tools and applications can be used to access and update the sas-code-examples repository. Detailed instructions are provided for each tool to accomplish the following steps:

documents.t: Various SAS tools and applications can be used to access and update the sas-code-examples repository. Detailed instructions are provided for each tool to accomplish the following steps: Create a forked copy of sas-code-examples Create a Git Profile Clone the repository Create/modify programs and update forked repository Merge changes into main repository Keep personal fork in sync with main repository
documents.s: Using SAS Tools to Access the Repository

documents.t: If you do not have a profile in GitHub, visit https://github.com/signup. Create an account with your email and a username of your choice. Access the public sas-code-examples repository. Click the down arrow next to Fork and select Create a new fork. It may be helpful to add a prefix to the repository name to distinguish it from the main repository, for example: name-sas-code-examples. The branch name cannot include spaces. Click Create fork. Confirm you are working in your branch, which is a personal copy of the repository.
documents.s: Create a forked copy of sas-code-examples

documents.t: In Enterprise Guide, select Tools > Manage Git connections > Profiles > + (Add). Enter the following information, then click OK > Close. Profile name: enter a name of your choice User name: your GitHub profile name Email: your email address Password: your GitHub password
documents.s: Create a Git Profile in SAS Enterprise Guide

documents.t: In your forked repository on GitHub.com, select the green Code button. On the Local tab, verify the HTTPS tab is selected. Click (Copy) to copy the repository reference. Return to Enterprise Guide. Select (Git Repositories) in the left pane and click Clone. Paste the repository URL copied previously from GitHub. Next, click . Create a new folder named sas-code-examples to store your local copy of the repository. Verify your GitHub profile is selected, then click Clone. Sas-code-examples is now listed in the Git Repositories pane, and a new tab opens. You can also double-click the repository name in the left pane to open it. This is where you can view the staged and unstaged changes in your local repository and pull or push changes to your external forked repository.
documents.s: Clone the repository in SAS Enterprise Guide

documents.t: In the Servers list in Enterprise Guide, navigate to the sas-code-examples folder where you cloned your personal forked version of the repository. You can open existing programs, make modifications, and save changes – just as you would any other local files. You can also add new programs. Any changes you make are saved only in your local repository. Select (Git Repositories) and double-click sas-code-examples to open the repository in a tab. Any programs that have been modified or created will be listed in the Unstaged Changes list. Select one or more programs from the list and use the down arrow icons to move them to the Staged Changes. View the program on the right to examine highlighted portions of the code that have been added or removed. Type a message in the Commit Comment box that describes the modifications made to the program(s), then click Commit. tip It is a good practice to stage one program at a time to provide an appropriate comment for the new commit. Only commit multiple programs at once if a single comment applies to all changes. Click Push to push the commits to your personal remote repository in GitHub. Return to your forked copy of the repository on GitHub.com and refresh the page to verify the changes have been synced.
documents.s: Create/modify programs and update personal repository

documents.t: At any point you can request to merge your personal repository changes with the official public repository. In GitHub, this is called a Pull Request (PR). Refresh the GitHub page for your personal forked repository. The following message indicates that you have updates in your branch that are not year in the public repository. Select Contribute > Open pull request. You may provide a description to explain the changes made. Your request will be reviewed to verify all contribution rules are followed and that there are no conflicts with other updates. warning Your contribution must meet the project's contribution guidelines. See CONTRIBUTING.md for details. The last line in the PR description must be the following text: Signed-off-by: Name <email.address>. Click Create pull request. You will likely see the following message, which can be ignored: The PR will go to the repository maintainers for approval. If there are issues with your requested changes, you may be asked in the comments of the PR to make further edits and recommit your file(s). Once all changes are approved, they will be merged into the main repository. You will see the following message in your PR:
documents.s: Merge changes into public repository

documents.t: tip You can continue to work with the same personal fork of the repository for future updates; however, it is very important to keep it in sync with the main project repository. This will help to avoid conflicts when making pull requests. In GitHub.com, check your branch for the following message that indicates there are updates in the public repository that have not been synced with your branch: Click Sync fork > Update branch. This will update your branch stored in GitHub. In Enterprise Guide, select (Git Repositories) and open your cloned sas-code-examples repository. Then click Pull to sync your local files with the remote repository.
documents.s: Keep personal fork in sync with main project repository

It may be helpful to add a prefix to the repository name to distinguish it from the main repository, for example: name-sas-code-examples. The branch name cannot include spaces. Click Create fork. Confirm you are working in your branch, which is a personal copy of the repository.
documents.s: Create a forked copy of sas-code-examples

documents.t: Open SAS Studio. If you do not see Git Repository in the left pane, click (More application options) and select View > Git Repository. From the Git Repository pane, click Create a Profile. Provide a profile name of your choice. Enter the user name and email associated with your GitHub profile. Browse to select your public and private SSH keys for authentication. See Creating a Git Profile for details. tip To view a demonstration of how to create and configure SSH keys with GitHub and SAS Studio, view Git Integration with SAS Studio.
documents.s: Create a Git Profile in SAS Studio

documents.t: In your forked repository on GitHub.com, select the green Code button. On the Local tab, select SSH. Click (Copy) to copy the repository reference. Return to SAS Studio. IN the Git Repository pane, click Clone a Repository. Navigate to a location with write access, then right-click the folder and select New folder. Name the folder sas-code-examples and click OK. Select (Git Repositories) in the left pane and click Clone. Paste the repository URL copied previously from GitHub. Next, click Browse. Create a new folder named sas-code-examples in a location of your choice. Select the new sas-code-examples folder and click OK. sas-code-examples is now listed in the Git Repositories pane, and a new tab opens. You can also double click the repository name in the left pane to open it. This is where you can view the staged and unstaged changes in your local repository and pull or push changes to the external Git repository.
documents.s: Clone the repository in SAS Studio

documents.t: In SAS Studio, click in the left pane to open the Explorer or SAS Server. Navigate to sas-code-examples folder where you cloned your personal forked version of the repository. You can open existing programs, make modifications, and save changes – just as you would any other local files. You can also add new programs. Any changes you make are saved only in your local repository. Select (Git Repositories) and double-click sas-code-examples to open the repository in a tab. Any programs that have been modified or created will be listed in the Unstaged Changes list. Select one or more programs from the list and use the down arrow icons to move them to the Staged Changes. View the program on the right to examine highlighted portions of the code that have been added or removed. Type a message in the Commit Comment box that describes the modifications made to the program(s), then click Commit. tip It is a good practice to stage one program at a time to provide an appropriate comment for the new commit. Only commit multiple programs at once if a single comment applies to all changes. Click Push Main to push the commits to your personal remote repository in GitHub. Return to your forked copy of the repository on GitHub.com and refresh the page to verify the changes have been synced.
